Title:
Avred Update: Advances in Reversing Microsoft Defender Signature Format

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post summarizes new reverse-engineering findings about Microsoft Defender’s signature database format and explains how they clarify Avred’s earlier detection behaviors.  
- It highlights that Defender signatures are composed of multiple weighted sub-rules and a score threshold; a detection triggers when accumulated sub-rule weights exceed the threshold.  
- This model explains “non-dominant” matches (multiple sub-rules contributing) versus “dominant” matches (a single sub-rule weight meeting/exceeding the threshold).  
- The post also details wildcard/placeholder constructs in signatures, showing that rules are not purely byte-exact and can tolerate variations (e.g., NOPs/register changes) via wildcard types.  
- It references `WdFilter.sys` as the kernel minifilter responsible for file scanning and provides examples translating wildcard constructs into YARA-like patterns.  
- Useful for malware analysts, red teamers, and detection engineers trying to understand Defender signature robustness and why naive byte-tweaks may fail.

Technical Focus:
- Microsoft Defender signature database reverse engineering
- Weighted sub-rule scoring and threshold-based triggering
- Wildcard/placeholder encoding (90 01–90 05 types)
- YARA-style representation of proprietary signature logic
- Windows Defender scanning path via `WdFilter.sys` minifilter

Use Cases:
- Explaining/triaging why specific binaries trigger Defender detections
- Designing more realistic signature-evasion experiments (and understanding their limits)
- Building tooling to parse/approximate Defender signature logic
- Creating defensive test cases to validate signature resilience to minor mutations

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender, Windows Defender, signature database, reverse engineering, avred, WdFilter.sys, minifilter driver, sub-rules, scoring threshold, weighted rules, dominant match, non-dominant match, wildcards, byte patterns, 90 01, 90 02, 90 03, 90 04, 90 05, YARA